ce:section.ce:para:
It is necessary to evaluate the feasibility of the fluorescent sensor for detecting analytes in actual samples. Hence, the spike recovery test was conducted to evaluate the accuracy and reproducibility of the proposed NS-CQDs and NS-CQDs/Cu2+ sensing platforms for detecting Cu2+ and GSH in human serum samples (Table 1
                         and Table 2
                        ). Remarkably, the assessment exhibited excellent analytical performance, with average recoveries for Cu2+ ranging from 97.66% to 103.92% and for GSH ranging from 97.56% to 103.29%. Furthermore, the relative standard deviations (RSDs) of Cu2+ and GSH were considerably lower, not exceeding 5.82% and 6.24%, respectively. In conclusion, the NS-CQDs and NS-CQDs/Cu2+ fluorescent sensing platform designed in this study can reliably monitor Cu2+ and GSH levels in human serum samples, with significant potential for practical applications.
